  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>When an LLM model crashes, compacts, or hits its context ceiling, the session dies. Starting a new session with a different model means losing everything — the context, the intent, the progress.</p>
  <p>Even a deliberate model switch (moving to a cheaper model for routine work, or a stronger model for a hard problem) requires rebuilding context from scratch.</p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>Type <code>:model gemini</code> mid-session. The OS builds a compact handoff that tells the new model what matters: which files are active, what decisions were made, what the current intent is.</p>
  <p>The new model boots with pointers to the project state, not a copy of the full context. It requests what it needs as it works.</p>

  <h2>What you see</h2>
  <pre><code>:model gemini            # switch to Gemini
# ... Gemini picks up where Claude left off ...

:model devstral          # switch to local model
# ... Devstral continues the work ...

:model claude            # switch back
# ... Claude resumes with full awareness of what happened ...</code></pre>

  <p>The handoff is invisible. The new model doesn't know it's continuing another model's work — it just has the right context to proceed.</p>

  <h2>Cross-vendor</h2>
  <p>Model switching works across vendors. The handoff is model-agnostic — it contains project state, not model-specific context. Tested paths include Claude → Gemini → DeepSeek → Claude with no context loss.</p>
</FeaturePage>
